ll bring fresh insights to this biography and more generally to Labour Party and socialist historiography, well-studied topics. The people Adams knew and the circles in which she travelled are particularly attractive features of this book. Foes thought her an awful woman: friends like George Bernard Shaw remembered the power of her oratory. Placed against the circumstances in which she lived and presented as part of a militant and anti-capitalist tradition within labour history, her life story contributes to new ways of seeing both socialist and feminist politics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aPolitical activistszGreat BritainvBiography. 0aSocialistszGreat BritainvBiography. 0aWomen political activistszGreat BritainvBiography. 0aWomen socialistszGreat BritainvBiography. 4amanchesterhive variable pricing textbooks. 7aEDUCATION / History.2bisacsh  aBritish socialism.  aBritish welfare state.  aFirst World War.  aLabour movement.  aMary Bridges Adams.  aeducation history.  apolitical activism.  apolitical history.  aprosopography.  asocial history.  asocialist movement.  aworking-class education.1 aMartin, Jane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez9783111283630oZDB-23-MUP40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526130464423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526130464/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-MUPc1986d2013